{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501905"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:36:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:36:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1806"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1806"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.01,0.03,0.42,0.43]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1806"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107538"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1806"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1806"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90008"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"10977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7644"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7655"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40114"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43106"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44347"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107538"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 41-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of non-productive cough and mild breathlessness. She has no significant medical history. She takes diclofenac occasionally for knee pain but no other regular medications. She is a non-smoker with a BMI of 23 kg/m\u00b2. She works as an accountant in a city office and lives with her husband and teenage son. They have a small dog as a pet. Her family members and dog are all well. She has not travelled overseas recently. Her hobby is tending to her rose garden.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Cardiorespiratory examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray is arranged (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rheumatoid lung disease","Tuberculosis","COVID-19 pneumonia","Hypersensitivity pneumonitis","Sarcoidosis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s history and chest X-ray (which demonstrated bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy) are consistent with a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Esarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E. It is a systemic disease that frequently affects the lungs, lymph nodes, eyes, skin, joints, liver, muscles, and the nervous system. Pulmonary involvement is documented in more than 90% of the patients. Acute sarcoidosis or L\u00f6fgren syndrome is characterised by erythema nodosum, bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy, polyarthritis, and uveitis. The most common pulmonary symptoms are progressive shortness of breath, non-productive cough, and chest discomfort. Chronic sputum production and haemoptysis are more frequent in advanced fibrocystic disease. Pulmonary hypertension or cor pulmonale is seen in more than 80% of patients with advanced fibrocystic sarcoidosis with pulmonary fibrosis. Granulomatous inflammation of the arterial and venous pulmonary vasculature is identified occasionally on biopsy, sometimes with little evidence of interstitial lung disease. Chest radiographs are abnormal in more than 90% of patients and also aid in the staging of the disease. Characteristic non-caseating granulomas can be found in biopsy specimens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome 50-70% of patients achieve remission in two to three years. Glucocorticoids are the mainstay of treatment, when indicated, such as in progressive pulmonary disease. Glucocorticoid-sparing agents and cytotoxic drugs such as methotrexate and biological agents such as TNF inhibitors can also be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid lung disease\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by interstitial lung diseases leading to fibrosis or rheumatoid nodules in the lung. The history in this patient is not suggestive of rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClassical X-ray findings in pulmonary \u003Cstrong\u003Etuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E are heterogenous but may include cavitary opacities in the apical segments and posterior segments of the upper and superior segments of the lower lobes. The history and chest X-ray in this patient are not suggestive of tuberculosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EX-ray findings in \u003Cstrong\u003ECOVID-19 pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E are the presence of peripheral ground glass opacities affecting any area of the lung, even patchy in multiple areas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypersensitivity pneumonitis\u003C/strong\u003E has variable presentation but is usually associated with exposure to known offending agents and recurrent symptoms. Characteristic radiological finding usually involves upper and middle lung zones.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sarcoidosis is a multi-system disease with pulmonary manifestations in more than 90% of patients","L\u00f6fgren syndrome is an acute presentation of sarcoidosis: hilar lymphadenopathy, arthritis, erythema nodosum, and uveitis","A biopsy can demonstrate non-caseating granuloma formation"],"references":["Stone J. Current diagnosis \u0026 treatment in rheumatology, fourth edition. 4th ed. Columbus, OH: McGraw-Hill Education; 2021","Ahmadzai H, Huang S, Steinfort C, et al. Sarcoidosis: a state of the art review from the Thoracic Society of Australia and New Zealand. Med J Aust. 2018;208(11):499-504. doi:10.5694/mja17.00610. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29719195/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90008"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1806"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19948"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19948"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9ea4a6b9-690e-43a3-a94e-46f32ca1d9e7.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9ea4a6b9-690e-43a3-a94e-46f32ca1d9e7.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":388,"height":364}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90008"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-01T08:43:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T08:47:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1806"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107538"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"